    # [Scene: Abandoned Pier & Kelp Nursery | Misty Dawn]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft, ascending strings that carry a cautious but steady warmth]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Creak of moorings, low gull calls, the distant thump of a delivery boat]
    "You feel the weight of your braided bracelet at the inside of your wrist, a familiar tightness that steadies rather than chokes. Elena's fingers are warm on your elbow as she guides you down the wooden"
    "ramp; her palm is steady, practical—the same hand that used to paint your storefront sign in wide, hurried strokes. The pier smells of brine and wet rope, a clean, honest stink that somehow smells like home"
    "after months of meetings and proposals."
    "Tomas Belmar stands at the center of the nursery, cap pulled low against the mist. When he speaks, the younger people quiet into something like listening: not duty, but respect. The kelp lines sway with him as if applauding."
    show tomas_belmar at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_belmar "When I was a boy, we'd know the safe tide by where the green stopped on the pilings. Kelp keeps a memory of the sea. We listen. We learn. We plant."
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "We build on what the bay remembers."
    show elena_torres at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_torres "You sound like the proposal, Mara. Less talk, more hammering."
    "You glance down at the yellow hooded raincoat you wear like armor—bright as a lighthouse against the grey. Your notebook is in your sling but closed; for now the plans live in the mouths and hands"
    "and muscle memory of the people gathered. Priya stands nearby with a tablet tucked under one arm, fingers stained with soil where she'd been tying plugs into a modular frame. Noah lingers close to the waterline,"
    "palms rubbed together as if he can will the sensors into obedience."
    hide tomas_belmar
    show priya_anand at left:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "If we document today's anchor test, the grant narrative writes itself. Time-stamped images, local volunteer roster, outcome metrics—Tomas's story is the center; the model just holds the thread together."
    hide mara_evans
    show noah_ros at right:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "I can loan a couple of prototypes—waterproof housings, pressure sensors. Promise: open schematics. I swear to you, Mara, no proprietary lock."
    "You watch him watch the scene: a man trying to make a place between a lab table and the pier. He looks like he wants to scale, to build something that will be measurable and sellable"
    "across districts, but also like he doesn't want to lose this particular quiet work to market forces. You catch his eye and give him a look that is both invitation and boundary."
    hide elena_torres
    show mara_evans at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "You stay with us today, Noah. This is community work—your tech is welcome, but only if it stays ours."

    noah_ros "Stay. Of course. I'll help anchor and log, not privatize."
    "His relief is small and human; you let yourself accept it. There's a comfort in choosing trust here—even precarious trust. Around you, people begin to organize: a roster goes up on a salvaged board, someone tapes a handwritten map beside it, children ferry off small pots of seedlings."
    hide priya_anand
    hide noah_ros
    hide mara_evans

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    "A little boy presses a strip of kelp into your palm. It's cool and slick, smelling of salt and the tang of growth. You close your fingers around it like a tiny relic and feel the community's pulse—messy, gritty, insistently alive."
    show tomas_belmar at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_belmar "They'll tell the city councils a story with their hands, not their speeches. Let them see work that can't be boxed into exhibits."
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "Then we make work they can't ignore."
    "You call a short assembly. Voices fold into one another—plans, jokes, the occasional sharp edge of worry. You feel the old instinct to make everything perfect bristle; instead you let imperfection be the currency of progress today."

    mara_evans "We map assets. Who can dive? Who has floats? Which shops can chip in nails and time? We list it loud and we list it true. If Arman Kade thinks a wall alone can hold a place—he hasn't met the people who bale and plant and stand watch."
    show elena_torres at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_torres "I can run a roster for small businesses. I know the bakers and the print shop. They'll help if they know the work shows their doors will stay."
    hide tomas_belmar
    show priya_anand at left:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "I'll translate it into a timeline and an application draft while you map. Grant bodies like concrete milestones: test anchors by Friday, deploy two modular bays by next week."
    hide mara_evans
    show noah_ros at right:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "And I'll log sensor outputs in real time. If we can show tidal attenuation and increased substrate with the planting bays, that's data that has teeth."

    "A woman in the back, face windburned and bright with a grin, calls out" "We have two divers and a boat. Tomas—you're on historical cues, but I know where to tie the buoys."
    "The chant that starts is small—an accidental chorus that turns into rhythm: names of tasks, shouted, answered. The sound is not polished; it's rooted. You feel the surge of it lift your insides like a tide lifting a hull."

    menu:
        "Let Tomas tell the assembly's story":
            "You step back, letting Tomas take the narrative. He speaks slow and everyone leans in; the work feels blessed by memory."
        "Take the floor and outline the technical plan":
            "You sketch the plan quickly on salvaged plywood; people nod at specifics—anchors, floats, volunteers—but the air tightens with responsibility."

