    "Both choices continue the progress of the project; teams adapt and the anchor test remains the focal point."
    "Noah comes back with a sensor array fixed to a buoy. He helps slip it under the modular bay as you both secure the anchor line. The first test is clumsy—seaweed tangles, a bolt slips—but when"
    "the line holds and the buoy settles, the cluster around you erupts into whoops. It feels, for one bright suspended second, like proof."

    mara_evans "That sound—it's the sound of the city still being ours."
    "A child runs up, cheeks flushed, hands sticky with kelp juice, and slams a damp frond into your palm again, as if insisting. You laugh, the sound raw and real."
    hide mara_evans
    show priya_anand at center:
        zoom 0.7

    priya_anand "Time-stamp confirmed. Pressure baseline established. Nora, can you log the volunteers and their hours?"
    "The board fills with names: divers, bakers, young carpenters who learned their trade in the old boathouse, an art teacher offering classes for kids in exchange for fence boards. The roster looks like the neighborhood itself—patched but whole."
    "As afternoon light slips into the gloss of early evening, someone hauls out a battered radio and plays a song you haven't heard since before the storm that took your storefront. People gather around it like it's a flame."
    "Noah Ríos sits next to you on a reclaimed crate, the sensor manual folded on his knee like a small, secret thing. He looks tired and hopeful and somehow more human here than he did at the council dais."
    hide elena_torres
    show noah_ros at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ros "You did the hard thing—and the brave thing. Refusing Arman Kade will make enemies. But it makes us something else: accountable, stubborn, visible."
    hide tomas_belmar
    show mara_evans at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_evans "I keep thinking about what it would mean to lose this—people scattered, stories untold. I couldn't—won't—let that be the price of 'security.'"

    noah_ros "Then don't let it be. We'll show them another way."

    mara_evans "Show them, and make sure it's real."
    "He squeezes your hand—quick, grounding. Not a promise of forever, but a promise of this day. The pier, the kelp, the people—each a small commitment."
    "Tomas Belmar comes forward with a thermos of coffee that has been through a dozen refills. He hands it to you like an old priest offering something holy."
    hide priya_anand
    show tomas_belmar at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_belmar "A community keeps its own heat. Keep this—it's for you—the person who called us here."
    "You hold the cup and step away for a beat, watching work continue: a woman measuring, a boy tying off a float, Elena negotiating with a hardware owner over a discount. The scene hums with a"
    "fierce hopeful rhythm—the kind of progress that tastes of salt and sawdust and the kind of stubborn love that refuses to look away."
    "Your notebook, finally, opens on your knee; you sketch a quick cross-section—anchors, planting beds, sensor placements. The lines are rough but right. You tuck the page back into the sling and stand."
    "You look at the council clock in the distance—its face small, clinical, ticking toward votes and hearings and deadlines you cannot avoid. But the pier beneath you is louder now, a living thing that will go to those meetings with a voice."
    hide noah_ros
    hide mara_evans
    hide tomas_belmar

